# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: real-user-monitoring-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] In the fields of information technology and systems management, **application performance management** (**APM**) is the monitoring and management of the performance and availability of software applications.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] APM strives to detect and diagnose complex application performance problems to maintain an expected level of service.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The term monitoring was replaced by many tool vendors by the term Observability.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Often, monitoring is seen as the technical process of data collection, whereas observability is seen as the capability to understand a systems behavior.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Two sets of performance metrics are closely monitored.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The first set of performance metrics defines the performance experienced by end-users of the application.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] One example of performance is average response times under peak load.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The second set of performance metrics measures the computational resources used by the application for the load, indicating whether there is adequate capacity to support the load, as well as possible locations of a performance bottleneck.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Measurement of these quantities establishes an empirical performance baseline for the application.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The baseline can then be used to detect changes in performance.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Changes in performance can be correlated with external events and subsequently used to predict future changes in application performance.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The use of APM is common for Web applications, which lends itself best to the more detailed monitoring techniques.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] In addition to measuring response time for a user, response times for components of a Web application can also be monitored to help pinpoint causes of delay.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] There also exist HTTP appliances that can decode transaction-specific response times at the Web server layer of the application.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Measuring application performance causes overhead, that might also influence the user experience.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The overhead can be reduced by several technical measures, including reducing the amount of monitored events and aggregation of data before serialization.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Since the first half of 2013, APM has entered into a period of intense competition in technology and strategy with a multiplicity of vendors and viewpoints.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] This has caused an upheaval in the marketplace with vendors from unrelated backgrounds (including network monitoring, systems management, application instrumentation, and web performance monitoring) adopting messaging around APM.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] As a result, the term APM has become diluted and has evolved into a concept for managing application performance across many diverse computing platforms, rather than a single market.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] With so many vendors to choose from, selecting one can be a challenge.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] It is important to evaluate each carefully to ensure its capabilities meet your needs.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Two challenges for implementing APM are (1) it can be difficult to instrument an application to monitor application performance, especially among components of an application, and (2) applications can be virtualized, which increases the variability of the measurements.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] To alleviate the first problem application service management (ASM) provides an application-centric approach, where business service performance visibility is a key objective.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The second aspect present in distributed, virtual and cloud-based applications poses a unique challenge for application performance monitoring because most of the key system components are no longer hosted on a single machine.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Each function is now likely to have been designed as an Internet service that runs on multiple virtualized systems.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The applications themselves are very likely to be moving from one system to another to meet service-level objectives and deal with momentary outages.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Applications themselves are becoming increasingly difficult to manage as they move toward highly distributed, multi-tier, multi-element constructs that in many cases rely on application development frameworks such as .NET or Java.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The APM Conceptual Framework was designed to help prioritize an approach on what to focus on first for quick implementation and overall understanding of the five-dimensional APM model.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The framework slide outlines three areas of focus for each dimension and describes their potential benefits.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Measuring the transit of traffic from user request to data and back again is part of capturing the end-user experience (EUE).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The outcome of this measuring is referred to as Real-time Application monitoring (aka Top-Down monitoring), which has two components, passive and active.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Passive monitoring is usually an agentless appliance implemented using network port mirroring.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] A key feature to consider is the ability to support multi-component analytics (e.g., database, client/browser).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Active monitoring, on the other hand, consists of synthetic probes and web robots predefined to report system availability and business transactions.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Active monitoring is a good complement to passive monitoring; together, these two components help provide visibility into application health during off-peak hours when transaction volume is low.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] When preparing to implement a runtime application architecture, it is necessary to ensure that up/down monitoring is in place for all nodes and servers within the environment (aka, bottom-up monitoring).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] This helps lay the foundation for event correlation and provides the basis for a general understanding of how network topologies interact with application architectures.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Focus on user-defined transactions or the URL page definitions that have some meaning to the business community.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] For example, if there are 200 to 300 unique page definitions for a given application, group them into 8–12 high-level categories.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] This allows for meaningful SLA reports, and provides trending information on application performance from a business perspective: start with broad categories and refine them over time.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] For a deeper understanding, see Business transaction management.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Deep dive component monitoring (DDCM) requires an agent installation and is generally targeted at middleware, focusing on web, application, and messaging servers.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] It should provide a real-time view of the J2EE and .NET stacks, tying them back to the user-defined business transactions.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] A robust monitor shows a clear path from code execution (e.g., spring and struts) to the URL rendered, and finally to the user request.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Since DDCM is closely related to the second dimension in the APM model, most products in this field also provide application discovery dependency mapping (ADDM) as part of their offering.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Optimizing for quality of user experience is key to the long-term success of any site on the web.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Whether you're a business owner, marketer, or developer, Web Vitals can help you quantify the experience of your site and identify opportunities to improve.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Web Vitals is an initiative by Google to provide unified guidance for quality signals that are essential to delivering a great user experience on the web.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Google has provided a number of tools over the years to measure and report on performance.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Some developers are experts at using these tools, while others have found the abundance of both tools and metrics challenging to keep up with.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Site owners shouldn't have to be performance experts to understand the quality of experience they are delivering to their users.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] The Web Vitals initiative aims to simplify the landscape, and help sites focus on the metrics that matter most, the **Core Web Vitals**.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Core Web Vitals are the subset of Web Vitals that apply to all web pages, should be measured by all site owners, and will be surfaced across all Google tools.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Each of the Core Web Vitals represents a distinct facet of the user experience, is measurable in the field, and reflects the real-world experience of a critical user-centric outcome.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] The metrics that make up Core Web Vitals will evolve over time.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] To ensure you're hitting the recommended target for these metrics for most of your users, a good threshold to measure is the **75th percentile** of page loads, segmented across mobile and desktop devices.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Tools that assess Core Web Vitals compliance should consider a page passing if it meets the recommended targets at the 75th percentile for all three of the Core Web Vitals metrics.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Metrics on the Core Web Vitals track go through a lifecycle consisting of three phases: experimental, pending, and stable.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] When a metric is initially developed and enters the ecosystem, it is considered an *experimental metric*.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] The purpose of the experimental phase is to assess a metric's fitness, first by exploring the problem to be solved, and possibly iterate on what previous metrics may have failed to address.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] For example, Interaction to Next Paint (INP) was initially developed as an experimental metric to address the runtime performance issues present on the web more comprehensively than First Input Delay (FID).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] The experimental phase of Core Web Vitals lifecycle is also intended to give flexibility in a metric's development by identifying bugs and even exploring changes to its initial definition.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] It's also the phase in which community feedback is most important.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] When the Chrome team determines that an experimental metric has received sufficient feedback and proven its efficacy, it becomes a *pending metric*.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] For example, INP was promoted in 2023 from experimental to pending status with the intent to eventually retire FID.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Pending metrics are held in this phase for a minimum of six months to give the ecosystem time to adapt.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Community feedback remains an important aspect of this phase, as more developers begin to use the metric.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] When a Core Web Vital candidate metric is finalized, it becomes a *stable metric*.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] This is when the metric can become a Core Web Vital.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Stable metrics are actively supported, and can be subject to bug fixes and definition changes.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Stable Core Web Vitals metrics won't change more than once per year.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Any change to a Core Web Vital will be clearly communicated in the metric's official documentation, as well as in the metric's changelog.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Core Web Vitals are also included in any assessments.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Google believes that the Core Web Vitals are critical to all web experiences.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] As a result, it is committed to surfacing these metrics in all of its popular tools.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] The following sections details which tools support the Core Web Vitals.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] The Chrome User Experience Report collects anonymized, real user measurement data for each Core Web Vital.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] This data enables site owners to quickly assess their performance without requiring them to manually instrument analytics on their pages, and powers tools like Chrome DevTools, PageSpeed Insights, and Search Console's Core Web Vitals report.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] The data provided by Chrome User Experience Report offers a quick way to assess the performance of sites, but it does not provide the detailed, per-pageview telemetry that is often necessary to accurately diagnose, monitor, and quickly react to regressions.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] As a result, we strongly recommend that sites set up their own real-user monitoring.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Each of the Core Web Vitals can be measured in JavaScript using standard web APIs.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] The easiest way to measure all the Core Web Vitals is to use the web-vitals JavaScript library, a small, production-ready wrapper around the underlying web APIs that measures each metric in a way that accurately matches how they're reported by all the Google tools listed earlier.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] With the web-vitals library, measuring each metric can be done by calling a single function.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] See the documentation for complete usage and API details.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Once you've configured your site to use the web-vitals library to measure and send your Core Web Vitals data to an analytics endpoint, the next step is to aggregate and report on that data to see if your pages are meeting the recommended thresholds for at least 75% of page visits.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] While some analytics providers have built-in support for Core Web Vitals metrics, even those that don't should include basic custom metric features that allow you to measure Core Web Vitals in their tool.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] For additional guidance on measuring these metrics using popular analytics services or your own in-house analytics tools, see Best practices for measuring Web Vitals in the field.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] While all of the Core Web Vitals are, first and foremost, field metrics, many of them are also measurable in the lab.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Lab measurement is the best way to test the performance of features during development—before they've been released to users.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] It's also the best way to catch performance regressions before they happen.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] While lab measurement is an essential part of delivering great experiences, it is not a substitute for field measurement.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] The performance of a site can substantially vary based on a user's device capabilities, their network conditions, what other processes may be running on the device, and how they're interacting with the page.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] In fact, each of the Core Web Vitals metrics can have its score affected by user interaction.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Only field measurement can accurately capture the complete picture.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] There are many ways to improve Core Web Vitals, and each approach comes with varying levels of impact, relevance, and ease of use for every situation.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Refer to The most effective ways to improve Core Web Vitals for a short list of the Chrome team's top recommendations.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] While the Core Web Vitals are the critical metrics for understanding and delivering a great user experience, there are other supporting metrics.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] These other metrics can serve as proxy—or as supplemental metrics for the three Core Web Vitals—to help capture a larger part of the experience or to aid in diagnosing a specific issue.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] For example, the metrics Time to First Byte (TTFB) and First Contentful Paint (FCP) are both vital aspects of the *loading* experience, and are both useful in diagnosing issues with LCP (slow server response times or render-blocking resources, respectively).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Similarly, a metric like Total Blocking Time (TBT) is a lab metrics is vital in catching and diagnosing potential *interactivity* issues that can impact INP.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] However, it is not part of the Core Web Vitals set because they are not field-measurable, nor do they reflect a user-centric outcome.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Web Vitals and Core Web Vitals represent the best available signals developers have today to measure quality of experience across the web, but these signals are not perfect and future improvements or additions should be expected.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] The **Core Web Vitals** are relevant to all web pages and featured across relevant Google tools.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Changes to these metrics will have wide-reaching impact; as such, developers should expect the definitions and thresholds of the Core Web Vitals to be stable, and updates to have prior notice and a predictable, annual cadence.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] The other Web Vitals are often context or tool specific, and may be more experimental than the Core Web Vitals.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] As such, their definitions and thresholds may change with greater frequency.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] For all Web Vitals, changes will be clearly documented in this public CHANGELOG.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Except as otherwise noted, the content of this page is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 License, and code samples are licensed under the Apache 2.0 License.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] For details, see the Google Developers Site Policies.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/articles-vitals] Java is a registered trademark of Oracle and/or its affiliates.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/real-user-monitoring] Organizations typically use RUM to test changes within the production environment or to anticipate behavioral changes in a website or application by using A/B testing or other techniques.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/real-user-monitoring] As technology shifts more and more to hybrid environments like cloud, fat clients, widgets, and apps, it becomes more and more important to monitor the usage of applications from within the client itself.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/real-user-monitoring] Real user monitoring is typically "passive monitoring" i.e., the RUM device collects web traffic without having any effect on the operation of the site.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/real-user-monitoring] In most cases, a form of JavaScript is injected into the page or native code within the application to provide feedback from the browser or client.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/real-user-monitoring] This data is collected from various individuals and consolidated.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/real-user-monitoring] RUM can be very helpful in identifying and troubleshooting last-mile issues.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/real-user-monitoring] RUM differs from synthetic monitoring in that it relies on actual people clicking on the page to take measurements rather than automated tests simply going over a given set of test steps.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/real-user-monitoring] RUM feature is available in various observability products such as Dynatrace, New Relic.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/real-user-monitoring] For example, New Relic provides RUM as a part of its Browser monitoring feature in which it captures, processes and visualizes the data in RUM dashboards.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] According to Nielsen Norman Group, 'user experience' includes all the aspects of the interaction between the end-user with the company, its services, and its products.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] The international standard on *ergonomics of human-system interaction*, ISO 9241, defines user experience as a "user's perceptions and responses that result from the use and/or anticipated use of a system, product or service".
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] According to the ISO definition, user experience includes all the users' emotions, beliefs, preferences, perceptions, physical and psychological responses, behaviors, and accomplishments that occur before, during, and after use.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] The ISO also lists three factors that influence user experience: the system, the user, and the context of use.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Note 3 of the standard hints that usability addresses aspects of user experience, e.g., "usability criteria can be used to assess aspects of user experience".
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] The standard does not go further in clarifying the relation between user experience and usability.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Clearly, the two are overlapping concepts, with usability including pragmatic aspects (getting a task done) and user experience focusing on users' feelings stemming from both pragmatic and hedonic aspects of the system.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Many practitioners use the terms interchangeably.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] The term "usability" pre-dates the term "user experience".
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Part of the reason the terms are often used interchangeably is that, as a practical matter, a user will, at a minimum, require sufficient usability to accomplish a task, while the feelings of the user may be less important, even to the user themselves.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Since usability is about getting a task done, aspects of user experience like information architecture and user interface can help or hinder a user's experience.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] If a website has "bad" information architecture and a user has a difficult time finding what they are looking for, then the user will not have an effective, efficient, and satisfying search.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] In addition to the ISO standard, there exist several other definitions for user experience.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Some of them have been studied by various researchers.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Early developments in user experience can be traced back to the Machine Age, which includes the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Frederick Winslow Taylor and Henry Ford explored ways to make human labor more efficient and productive.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Taylor's research into the efficiency of interactions between workers and their tools is the earliest example that resembles today's user experience fundamentals.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] The term *user experience* was brought to wider knowledge by Donald Norman in the mid-1990s.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] He never intended the term "user experience" to be applied only to the affective aspects of usage.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] A review of his earlier work suggests that the term "user experience" was used to signal a shift to include affective factors, along with the pre-requisite behavioral concerns, which had been traditionally considered in the field.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Many usability practitioners continue to research and attend to affective factors associated with end-users, and have been doing so for years, long before the term "user experience" was introduced in the mid-1990s.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] In an interview in 2007, Norman discusses the widespread use of the term "user experience" and its imprecise meaning as a consequence thereof.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] In website design, it was important to combine the interests of different stakeholders: marketing, branding, visual design, and usability.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Marketing and branding people needed to enter the interactive world where usability was important.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Usability people needed to take marketing, branding, and aesthetic needs into account when designing websites.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] User experience provided a platform to cover the interests of all stakeholders: making websites easy to use, valuable, and effective for visitors.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] This is why several early user experience publications focus on website user experience.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] The field of user experience represents an expansion and extension of the field of usability to include the holistic perspective of how a person feels about using a system.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] The focus is on pleasure and value as well as on performance.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] The exact definition, framework, and elements of user experience are still evolving.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] User experience of an interactive product or a website is usually measured by a number of methods, including questionnaires, focus groups, observed usability tests, user journey mapping and other methods.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] A freely available questionnaire (available in several languages) is the User Experience Questionnaire (UEQ).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] The development and validation of this questionnaire is described in a computer science essay published in 2008.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Higher levels of user experience have been linked to increased effectiveness of digital health interventions targeting improvements in physical activity, nutrition, mental health and smoking.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Google Ngram Viewer shows wide use of the term starting in the 1930s.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] "He suggested that more follow-up in the field would be welcomed by the user, and would be a means of incorporating the results of the user's experience into the design of new machines." Use of the term in relation to computer software also pre-dates Norman.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Many factors can influence a user's experience with a system.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] To address the variety, factors influencing user experience have been classified into three main categories: the user's state and previous experience, system properties, and the usage context (situation).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Understanding representative users, working environments, interactions, and emotional reactions helps in designing the system during User experience design.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] The overall user experience is not simply a sum of smaller interaction experiences, because some experiences are more salient than others.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Overall user experience is also influenced by factors outside the actual interaction episode: brand, pricing, friends' opinions, reports in the media, etc.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] One branch of user experience research focuses on emotions.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] This includes momentary experiences during interaction: designing effective interaction and evaluating emotions.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Another branch is interested in understanding the long-term relationship between user experience and product appreciation.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] The industry sees a good overall user experience with a company's products as critical for securing brand loyalty and enhancing the growth of the customer base.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] All temporal levels of user experience (momentary, episodic, and long-term) are important, but the methods to design and evaluate these levels can be very different.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] While user experience has become an essential part of design and product development, it has also attracted criticism and ethical scrutiny.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Focusing on user satisfaction and business goals may lead to harmful design choices, unintentional accessibility gaps, or user manipulation.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] These conflicts suggest that UX has room to become a more responsible and inclusive practice.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] One major critique of UX is the conflict between designing for user benefit and designing for business objectives.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] UX decisions are often shaped by financial incentives rather than users’ well-being.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] This leads to design choices that prioritize growth over ethics, for example, features that encourage excessive screen time, collect unnecessary personal data (also known as *privacy zuckering*), or make it difficult for users to unsubscribe from services (also known as *forced continuity*).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] While trying to increase profits, it may actually increase economic harm and reduce market efficiency.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Critics argue that such practices compromise the foundational goal of UX, which is to improve the user's experience, not exploit it.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Companies can be held accountable for their design choices by prioritizing user interests.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] For instance, ensuring price transparency helps users make informed decisions.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Organizations can also align design decisions with user well-being by evaluating qualitative outcomes, like how a product contributes to users’ happiness or mental health, instead of relying solely on engagement metrics.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] By making business success dependent on user trust and satisfaction, rather than engagement metrics alone, organizations can create sustainable products that support both profitability and user well-being.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Another major ethical concern in UX is the use of dark patterns, interface designs that intentionally mislead or manipulate users into taking actions they might not otherwise choose.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Examples include use of checkboxes to opt out rather than opt in (double negatives), confusing cancellation processes, or “confirm” buttons that lead to unintended purchases.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Scholars from Princeton and Purdue University have argued that dark patterns represent a misuse of UX principles, using psychological insights and interface design against user interests.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] One proposed solution to the problem of dark patterns is to focus on how to distinguish manipulative patterns from legitimate persuasion.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] For example, researchers at Princeton suggest using guidelines to evaluate when a design crosses the line into manipulation.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Researchers from Purdue University instead argue that ethical awareness cannot rely solely on codes of conduct but should instead focus on the designer’s intent, judgment, and ongoing responsibility.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Another area of criticism concerns accessibility and inclusivity in UX design.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Although improving usability is a central aim of UX, many products and services continue to overlook the needs of people with disabilities, older users, or those from different cultural and linguistic backgrounds.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] This exclusion can occur due to implicit bias in design teams, lack of diverse user testing, or assumptions about “average” users.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] To address these gaps, experts recommend adopting inclusive design principles throughout the development process.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] This includes conducting accessibility audits, following the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG), and involving users with disabilities in usability testing to ensure products meet real-world needs.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Expanding user research to include diverse groups can also uncover assumptions and biases early.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Additionally, ongoing education about unconscious bias for design teams can help create products that reflect a broader range of user experiences.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] Developer experience (DX) is a user experience from a developer's point of view.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] It is defined by the tools, processes, and software that a developer uses when interacting with a product or system while in the process of producing another one, such as in software development.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/user-experience] DX has had increased attention paid to it, especially in businesses that primarily offer software as a service to other businesses, where ease of use is a key differentiator in the market.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The goal of A/B testing is to identify and suggest changes to web pages that increase or maximize the effect of a statistically tested result of interest.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Each stage impacts or can impact (i.e., drives) the stage preceding or following it.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] So, sometimes the data that is available for collection impacts the online strategy.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Other times, the online strategy affects the data collected.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] There are at least two categories of web analytics, *off-site* and *on-site* web analytics.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] In the past, web analytics has been used to refer to on-site visitor measurement.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] However, this meaning has become blurred, mainly because vendors are producing tools that span both categories.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Many different vendors provide on-site web analytics software and services.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] There are two main technical ways of collecting the data.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The first and traditional method, *server log file analysis*, reads the logfiles in which the web server records file requests by browsers.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The second method, *page tagging*, uses JavaScript embedded in the webpage to make image requests to a third-party analytics-dedicated server, whenever a webpage is rendered by a web browser or, if desired, when a mouse click occurs.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Both collect data that can be processed to produce web traffic reports.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] There are no globally agreed definitions within web analytics as the industry bodies have been trying to agree on definitions that are useful and definitive for some time, that is to say, metrics in tools and products from different companies may have different ways of measuring and counting.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] As a result, the same metric name may represent the different meaning of data.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The main bodies who have had input in this area have been the IAB (Interactive Advertising Bureau), JICWEBS (The Joint Industry Committee for Web Standards in the UK and Ireland), and The DAA (Digital Analytics Association), formally known as the WAA (Web Analytics Association, US).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Off-site web analytics is based on open data analysis, social media exploration, and share of voice on web properties.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] It is usually used to understand how to market a site by identifying the keywords tagged to this site, either from social media or from other websites.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The fundamental goal of web analytics is to collect and analyze data related to web traffic and usage patterns.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Network-level and server-generated data associated with HTTP requests: not part of an HTTP request, but it is required for successful request transmissions - for example, the IP address of a requester.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Application-level data sent with HTTP requests: generated and processed by application-level programs (such as JavaScript, PHP, and ASP.Net), including sessions and referrals.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] These are usually captured by internal logs rather than public web analytics services.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] External data: can be combined with on-site data to help augment the website behaviour data described above and interpret web usage.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] For example, IP addresses are usually associated with Geographic regions and internet service providers, e-mail open and click-through rates, direct mail campaign data, sales, lead history, or other data types as needed.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Web servers records some of their transactions in a log file.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] It was soon realized that these log files could be read by a program to provide data on the popularity of the website.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] In the early 1990s, website statistics consisted primarily of counting the number of client requests (or *hits*) made to the web server.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] This was a reasonable method initially since each website often consisted of a single HTML file.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] However, with the introduction of images in HTML, and websites that spanned multiple HTML files, this count became less useful.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The first true commercial Log Analyzer was released by IPRO in 1994.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Two units of measure were introduced in the mid-1990s to gauge more accurately the amount of human activity on web servers.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] These were *page views* and *visits* (or *sessions*).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] A *page view* was defined as a request made to the web server for a page, as opposed to a graphic, while a *visit* was defined as a sequence of requests from a uniquely identified client that expired after a certain amount of inactivity, usually 30 minutes.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The emergence of search engine spiders and robots in the late 1990s, along with web proxies and dynamically assigned IP addresses for large companies and ISPs, made it more difficult to identify unique human visitors to a website.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Log analyzers responded by tracking visits by cookies, and by ignoring requests from known spiders.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The extensive use of web caches also presented a problem for log file analysis.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] If a person revisits a page, the second request will often be retrieved from the browser's cache, so no request will be received by the web server.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] This means that the person's path through the site is lost.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Caching can be defeated by configuring the web server, but this can result in degraded performance for the visitor and a bigger load on the servers.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Concerns about the accuracy of log file analysis in the presence of caching, and the desire to be able to perform web analytics as an outsourced service, led to the second data collection method, page tagging or "web beacons".
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] In the mid-1990s, Web counters were commonly seen — these were images included in a web page that showed the number of times the image had been requested, which was an estimate of the number of visits to that page.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] In the late 1990s, this concept evolved to include a small invisible image instead of a visible one, and, by using JavaScript, to pass along with the image request certain information about the page and the visitor.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] This information can then be processed remotely by a web analytics company, and extensive statistics generated.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The web analytics service also manages the process of assigning a cookie to the user, which can uniquely identify them during their visit and in subsequent visits.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Cookie acceptance rates vary significantly between websites and may affect the quality of data collected and reported.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Collecting website data using a third-party data collection server (or even an in-house data collection server) requires an additional DNS lookup by the user's computer to determine the IP address of the collection server.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] On occasion, delays in completing successful or failed DNS lookups may result in data not being collected.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] With the increasing popularity of Ajax-based solutions, an alternative to the use of an invisible image is to implement a call back to the server from the rendered page.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] In this case, when the page is rendered on the web browser, a piece of JavaScript code would call back to the server and pass information about the client that can then be aggregated by a web analytics company.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Both logfile analysis programs and page tagging solutions are readily available to companies that wish to perform web analytics.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] In some cases, the same web analytics company will offer both approaches.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The question then arises of which method a company should choose.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] There are advantages and disadvantages to each approach.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Logfile analysis is almost always performed in-house.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Page tagging can be performed in-house, but it is more often provided as a third-party service.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The economic difference between these two models can also be a consideration for a company deciding which to purchase.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Which solution is cheaper to implement depends on the amount of technical expertise within the company, the vendor chosen, the amount of activity seen on the websites, the depth and type of information sought, and the number of distinct websites needing statistics.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Regardless of the vendor solution or data collection method employed, the cost of web visitor analysis and interpretation should also be included.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] That is the cost of turning raw data into actionable information.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] This can be from the use of third-party consultants, the hiring of an experienced web analyst, or the training of a suitable in-house person.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] A cost-benefit analysis can then be performed.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] For example, what revenue increase or cost savings can be gained by analyzing the web visitor data?
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Some companies produce solutions that collect data through both log files and page tagging and can analyze both kinds.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] By using a hybrid method, they aim to produce more accurate statistics than either method on its own.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] With IP geolocation, it is possible to track visitors' locations.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Using an IP geolocation database or API, visitors can be geolocated to city, region, or country level.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] IP Intelligence, or Internet Protocol (IP) Intelligence, is a technology that maps the Internet and categorizes IP addresses by parameters such as geographic location (country, region, state, city and postcode), connection type, Internet Service Provider (ISP), proxy information, and more.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The first generation of IP Intelligence was referred to as geotargeting or geolocation technology.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Click analytics, also known as Clickstream is a special type of web analytics that gives special attention to clicks.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Commonly, click analytics focuses on on-site analytics.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] An editor of a website uses click analytics to determine the performance of his or her particular site, with regard to where the users of the site are clicking.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Also, click analytics may happen in real-time or "unreal"-time, depending on the type of information sought.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Typically, front-page editors on high-traffic news media sites will want to monitor their pages in real-time, to optimize the content.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Editors, designers or other types of stakeholders may analyze clicks on a wider time frame to help them assess the performance of writers, design elements advertisements etc.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Data about clicks may be gathered in at least two ways.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Ideally, a click is "logged" when it occurs, and this method requires some functionality that picks up relevant information when the event occurs.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Alternatively, one may institute the assumption that a page view is a result of a click, and therefore log a simulated click that led to that page view.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Customer lifecycle analytics is a visitor-centric approach to measuring.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Page views, clicks and other events (such as API calls, access to third-party services, etc.) are all tied to an individual visitor instead of being stored as separate data points.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Customer lifecycle analytics attempts to connect all the data points into a marketing funnel that can offer insights into visitor behaviour and website optimization.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Common metrics used in customer lifecycle analytics include customer acquisition cost (CAC), customer lifetime value (CLV), customer churn rate, and customer satisfaction scores.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Other methods of data collection are sometimes used.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Packet sniffing collects data by sniffing the network traffic passing between the web server and the outside world.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Packet sniffing involves no changes to the web pages or web servers.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Integrating web analytics into the web server software is also possible.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Both these methods claim to provide better real-time data than other methods.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The hotel problem is generally the first problem encountered by a web analytics user.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The problem is that the unique visitors for each day in a month do not add up to the same total as the unique visitors for that month.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] This appears to be a problem for inexperienced users in whatever analytics software they are using.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] It is a simple property of the metric definitions.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The way to picture the situation is by imagining a hotel.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The hotel has two rooms (Room A and Room B).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] As the table shows, the hotel has two unique users each day over three days.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The sum of the totals concerning the days is therefore six.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] During the period each room has had two unique users.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The sum of the totals concerning the rooms is therefore four.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Only three visitors have been in the hotel over this period.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The problem is that a person who stays in a room for two nights will get counted twice if they are counted once on each day, but are only counted once if the total for the period is looked at.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Any software for web analytics will sum these correctly for the chosen period, thus leading to the problem when a user tries to compare the totals.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] As the internet has matured, the proliferation of automated bot traffic has become an increasing problem for the reliability of web analytics.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] As bots traverse the internet, they render web documents in ways similar to organic users, and as a result may incidentally trigger the same code that web analytics use to count traffic.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Jointly, this incidental triggering of web analytics events impacts the interpretability of data and inferences made upon that data.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] IPM provided a proof of concept of how Google Analytics as well as their competitors are easily triggered by common bot deployment strategies.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Historically, vendors of page-tagging analytics solutions have used third-party cookies sent from the vendor's domain instead of the domain of the website being browsed.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Third-party cookies can handle visitors who cross multiple unrelated domains within the company's site since the cookie is always handled by the vendor's servers.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] However, third-party cookies in principle allow tracking an individual user across the sites of different companies, allowing the analytics vendor to collate the user's activity on sites where he provided personal information with his activity on other sites where he thought he was anonymous.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Although web analytics companies deny doing this, other companies such as companies supplying banner ads have done so.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Privacy concerns about cookies have therefore led a noticeable minority of users to block or delete third-party cookies.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] In 2005, some reports showed that about 28% of Internet users blocked third-party cookies and 22% deleted them at least once a month.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Most vendors of page tagging solutions have now moved to provide at least the option of using first-party cookies (cookies assigned from the client subdomain).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] When web analytics depend on cookies to identify unique visitors, the statistics are dependent on a persistent cookie to hold a unique visitor ID.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] When users delete cookies, they usually delete both first- and third-party cookies.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] If this is done between interactions with the site, the user will appear as a first-time visitor at their next interaction point.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Without a persistent and unique visitor ID, conversions, click-stream analysis, and other metrics dependent on the activities of a unique visitor over time cannot be accurate.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Cookies are used because IP addresses are not always unique to users and may be shared by large groups or proxies.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] In some cases, the IP address is combined with the user agent to more accurately identify a visitor if cookies are not available.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] However, this only partially solves the problem because often users behind a proxy server have the same user agent.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Other methods of uniquely identifying a user are technically challenging and would limit the trackable audience or would be considered suspicious.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Cookies reach the lowest common denominator without using technologies regarded as spyware and having cookies enabled/active leads to security concerns.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which came into force in May 2018, requires that websites obtain explicit and affirmative consent from users before collecting analytics data.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Following its enforcement, a measurable decline in recorded EU web traffic and user engagement was observed across websites, attributed to both changes in actual user behaviour and restrictions on what data could lawfully be collected.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] The regulation was also associated with a reduction in the use of privacy-invasive tracking technologies, while analytics trackers were only marginally affected.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Third-party information gathering is subject to any network limitations and security applied.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] Countries, Service Providers and Private Networks can prevent site visit data from going to third parties.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] All the methods described above (and some other methods not mentioned here, like sampling) have the central problem of being vulnerable to manipulation (both inflation and deflation).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] This means these methods are imprecise and insecure (in any reasonable model of security).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-analytics] This issue has been addressed in several papers, but to date the solutions suggested in these papers remain theoretical.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] A **web page**, or **webpage**, is a Web document that is accessed in a web browser.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] A website typically consists of many web pages linked together under a common domain name.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] The term "web page" is therefore a metaphor of paper pages bound together into a book.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] Each web page is identified by a distinct Uniform Resource Locator (URL).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] When the user inputs a URL into their web browser, the browser retrieves the necessary content from a web server and then transforms it into an interactive visual representation on the user's screen.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] If the user clicks or taps a link, the browser repeats this process to load the new URL, which could be part of the current website or a different one.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] The browser has features, such as the address bar, that indicate which page is displayed.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] The core element is a text file written in the HyperText Markup Language (HTML).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] This specifies the content of the page, including images and video.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) specify the presentation of the page.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] CSS rules can be in separate text files or embedded within the HTML file.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] The vast majority of pages have JavaScript programs, enabling a wide range of behavior.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] The newer WebAssembly language can also be used as a supplement.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] The most sophisticated web pages, known as web apps, combine these elements in a complex manner.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] From the perspective of server-side website deployment, there are two types of web pages: static and dynamic.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] Static pages are retrieved from the web server's file system without any modification, while dynamic pages must be created by the server on the fly, typically reading from a database to fill out a template, before being sent to the user's browser.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] An example of a dynamic page is a search engine results page.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] The Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) is the way a web browser retrieves webpage content from a website.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] HTTP has two optional security features: encrypted mode (HTTPS) greatly reduces the possibility of eavesdropping by a third party, while Content Security Policy protects against cross-site scripting attacks.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-page] Both features are supported by mainstream web browsers, and many websites use them.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Faster website download speeds have been shown to increase visitor retention and loyalty and user satisfaction, especially for users with slow internet connections and those on mobile devices.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Web performance also leads to less data travelling across the web, which in turn lowers a website's power consumption and environmental impact.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Some aspects which can affect the speed of page load include browser/server cache, image optimization, and encryption (for example SSL), which can affect the time it takes for pages to render.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] The performance of the web page can be improved through techniques such as multi-layered cache, light weight design of presentation layer components and asynchronous communication with server side components.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] In the first decade or so of the web's existence, web performance improvement was focused mainly on optimizing website code and pushing hardware limitations.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] According to the 2002 book *Web Performance Tuning* by Patrick Killelea, some of the early techniques used were to use simple servlets or CGI, increase server memory, and look for packet loss and retransmission.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Although these principles now comprise much of the optimized foundation of internet applications, they differ from current optimization theory in that there was much less of an attempt to improve the browser display speed.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Steve Souders coined the term "web performance optimization" in 2004.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] At that time Souders made several predictions regarding the impact that WPO as an "emerging industry" would bring to the web, such as websites being fast by default, consolidation, web standards for performance, environmental impacts of optimization, and speed as a differentiator.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] One major point that Souders made in 2007 is that at least 80% of the time that it takes to download and view a website is controlled by the front-end structure.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] This lag time can be decreased through awareness of typical browser behavior, as well as of how HTTP works.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Web performance optimization improves user experience (UX) when visiting a website and therefore is highly desired by web designers and web developers.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] They employ several techniques that streamline web optimization tasks to decrease web page load times.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] This process is known as front end optimization (FEO) or content optimization.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] In addition to the techniques listed below, the use of a content delivery network—a group of proxy servers spread across various locations around the globe—is an efficient delivery system that chooses a server for a specific user based on network proximity.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Typically the server with the quickest response time is selected.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Web browsers open separate Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) connections for each Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) request submitted when downloading a web page.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] These requests total the number of page elements required for download.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] However, a browser is limited to opening only a certain number of simultaneous connections to a single host.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] To prevent bottlenecks, the number of individual page elements are reduced using resource consolidation whereby smaller files (such as images) are bundled together into one file.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] This reduces HTTP requests and the number of "round trips" required to load a web page.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Web pages are constructed from code files such JavaScript and Hypertext Markup Language (HTML).
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] As web pages grow in complexity, so do their code files and subsequently their load times.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] File compression can reduce code files by about 40 percent, thereby improving site responsiveness.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Web Caching Optimization reduces server load, bandwidth usage and latency.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] CDNs use dedicated web caching software to store copies of documents passing through their system.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Many website platforms, such as SiteGround, IONOS, Wix, and Hostinger, rely on global CDNs and caching technologies to deliver faster page loads across different geographical regions.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Subsequent requests from the cache may be fulfilled should certain conditions apply.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Web caches are located on either the client side (forward position) or web-server side (reverse position) of a CDN.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Web browsers are also able to store content for re-use through the HTTP cache or web cache.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Requests web browsers make are typically routed to the HTTP cache to validate if a cached response may be used to fulfill a request.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] If such a match is made, the response is fulfilled from the cache.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] This can be helpful for reducing network latency and costs associated with data-transfer.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] The HTTP cache is configured using request and response headers.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Code minification distinguishes discrepancies between codes written by web developers and how network elements interpret code.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Minification removes comments and extra spaces as well as crunch variable names in order to minimize code, decreasing files sizes by as much as 60%.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] In addition to caching and compression, lossy compression techniques (similar to those used with audio files) remove non-essential header information and lower original image quality on many high resolution images.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] These changes, such as pixel complexity or color gradations, are transparent to the end-user and do not noticeably affect perception of the image.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Another technique is the replacement of raster graphics with resolution-independent vector graphics.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Vector substitution is best suited for simple geometric images.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Lazy loading of images and video reduces initial page load time, initial page weight, and system resource usage, all of which have positive impacts on website performance.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] It is used to defer initialization of an object right until the point at which it is needed.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] The browser loads the images in a page or post when they are needed such as when the user scrolls down the page and not all images at once, which is the default behavior, and naturally, takes more time.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Since web browsers use multiple TCP connections for parallel user requests, congestion and browser monopolization of network resources may occur.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Because HTTP/1 requests come with associated overhead, web performance is impacted by limited bandwidth and increased usage.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Instead of a website's hosting server, CDNs are used in tandem with HTTP/2 in order to better serve the end-user with web resources such as images, JavaScript files and Cascading Style Sheet (CSS) files since a CDN's location is usually in closer proximity to the end-user.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] In recent years, several metrics have been introduced that help developers measure various aspects of the performance of their websites.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Modules to measure metrics such as TTFB, FCP, LCP, FP etc are provided with major frontend JavaScript libraries such as React, NuxtJS and Vue.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Google publishes a library, the core-web-vitals library that allows for easy measurement of these metrics in frontend applications.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] In addition to this, Google also provides the Lighthouse, a Chrome dev-tools component and PageSpeed Insight a site that allows developers to measure and compare the performance of their website with Google's recommended minimums and maximums.
[src:real-user-monitoring-deep/web-performance] In addition to this, tools such as the Network Monitor by Mozilla Firefox help provide insight into network-level slowdowns that might occur during transmission of data.
